<!-- ══════════════════════════════════════════════
     P33 PRACTICAL
══════════════════════════════════════════════ -->

<section id="p33" class="section active">
  <div class="sec-header">
    <span class="sec-num">01 —</span>
    <h2 class="sec-title">Paper 33 · Perfect Practical</h2>
    <span class="sec-badge badge-urgent">28 APR · FIRST EXAM</span>
  </div>

  <!-- MASTER CHECKLIST -->

  <div class="card card-red">
    <p class="card-title">Master Entry Checklist — Before You Begin</p>
    <ul class="checklist">
      <li><span class="check-icon">✓</span><span class="check-label">Read the <strong>entire question</strong> before touching equipment. Identify the two variables and their relationship.</span></li>
      <li><span class="check-icon">✓</span><span class="check-label">Write column headings with <strong>quantity / unit</strong> (e.g., <code>l / m</code> or <code>T² / s²</code>). Missing units = lost marks.</span></li>
      <li><span class="check-icon">✓</span><span class="check-label">Decide <strong>significant figures</strong> before taking readings — rule: match the precision of the instrument.</span></li>
      <li><span class="check-icon">✓</span><span class="check-label">Take a <strong>minimum of 6 sets</strong> of readings; the mark scheme requires 6 for data marks.</span></li>
      <li><span class="check-icon">✓</span><span class="check-label">Spread your data <strong>over the full range</strong> of the independent variable. Clustered points lose graph marks.</span></li>
      <li><span class="check-icon">✓</span><span class="check-label">Check for <strong>anomalous points</strong> — circle them on the graph, <em>do not</em> use them for best-fit line.</span></li>
      <li><span class="check-icon">✓</span><span class="check-label">Use a <strong>sharp pencil</strong> for plotting — examiner marks to nearest half-square.</span></li>
      <li><span class="check-icon">✓</span><span class="check-label">Draw the <strong>best-fit straight line</strong> with a ruler; it should have roughly equal points on both sides.</span></li>
      <li><span class="check-icon">✓</span><span class="check-label">Gradient triangle: use <strong>at least half the drawn line</strong>, read co-ordinates from the line (not from data points).</span></li>
      <li><span class="check-icon">✓</span><span class="check-label">Quote gradient/intercept to <strong>2–3 significant figures</strong> with correct units.</span></li>
    </ul>
  </div>

  <!-- QUESTION 1A: SIGNIFICANT FIGURES -->

  <h4>Question 1 · Part A — Significant Figures in Tables</h4>
  <div class="card card-gold">
    <p class="card-title">The Cambridge S.F. Rules — Memorise These Exactly</p>
    <div class="rule-box">
      <div class="rule-title">Rule 1 — Raw Measurements</div>
      Match the precision of the instrument.<br>
      Ruler (mm) → record to nearest mm → <code>23.4 cm</code> ✓ &nbsp;|&nbsp; <code>23 cm</code> ✗<br>
      Stopwatch (0.01 s) → record as <code>12.34 s</code> ✓
    </div>
    <div class="rule-box">
      <div class="rule-title">Rule 2 — Calculated Columns</div>
      Must be consistent with raw data. If raw data is 3 s.f., calculated column must be 3 s.f.<br>
      Never quote <em>more</em> s.f. than the <em>least precise</em> measurement used.
    </div>
    <div class="rule-box">
      <div class="rule-title">Rule 3 — Consistency Down a Column</div>
      All values in a column must have the <strong>same number of decimal places</strong>.<br>
      e.g. if first entry is <code>1.23</code>, entry cannot be <code>1.4</code> or <code>1.234</code>
    </div>
    <div class="rule-box">
      <div class="rule-title">Rule 4 — Logarithm Columns</div>
      If a column is <code>lg(d/m)</code>, the number of decimal places = s.f. of raw value.<br>
      e.g. <code>d = 0.230 m</code> (3 s.f.) → <code>lg d = −0.638</code> (3 d.p.)
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- QUESTION 1B: HALF-SQUARE RULE -->

  <h4>Question 1 · Part B — The "Half-Square" Plotting Rule</h4>
  <div class="card card-blue">
    <p class="card-title">Plotting Precision — This Costs Students Easy Marks</p>
    <ul class="checklist">
      <li><span class="check-icon">✓</span><span class="check-label"><strong>Half-square accuracy:</strong> Each plotted point must be within <code>±½</code> of a small grid square of its true position. On standard 2 mm graph paper, this means within <strong>±1 mm</strong>.</span></li>
      <li><span class="check-icon">✓</span><span class="check-label"><strong>Plot size:</strong> Use a small cross or dot with a circle. Do NOT use large dots or blobs — these are ambiguous to the nearest mm.</span></li>
      <li><span class="check-icon">✓</span><span class="check-label"><strong>Scale choice:</strong> Scales must allow the graph to occupy at least <strong>half the grid</strong> in both x and y directions. Avoid awkward scales like ×3 or ×7 — use ×1, ×2, ×4, ×5, ×10.</span></li>
      <li><span class="check-icon">✓</span><span class="check-label"><strong>Scale origin:</strong> The origin does NOT need to be (0,0). A false origin is fine and often gives a better-spread graph.</span></li>
      <li><span class="check-icon">✓</span><span class="check-label"><strong>Axis labels:</strong> Both axes must be labelled with quantity AND unit. <code>v² / m²s⁻²</code> not just <code>v²</code>.</span></li>
      <li><span class="check-icon">✓</span><span class="check-label"><strong>Best-fit line:</strong> Must be a single, thin, continuous straight line. Do NOT join dots. The line is rejected if it bends at any point.</span></li>
      <li><span class="check-icon">✓</span><span class="check-label"><strong>Gradient read-off:</strong> Co-ordinates used must be <em>on the line</em>, read to the nearest half-square, and the triangle must span ≥ half the drawn line length.</span></li>
    </ul>
