  <h4>Question 2 · Evaluation — Standard Limitations & Mark-Scheme Improvements</h4>
  <p>The examiner awards marks only for <em>specific, method-linked</em> improvements. Vague answers such as "use better equipment" or "be more careful" score zero. Below are the 6 standard categories with model answers.</p>

  <div class="card card-purple" style="padding: 0; overflow: hidden;">
    <table class="data-table" style="margin: 0;">
      <thead>
        <tr>
          <th class="td-num">#</th>
          <th>Limitation (Problem)</th>
          <th>Mark-Scheme Improvement</th>
        </tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr>
          <td class="td-num">1</td>
          <td class="td-limit"><strong>Parallax Error</strong><br><span style="color:var(--muted);font-size:12px;">Eye not level with scale / ruler not touching object.</span></td>
          <td class="td-improve">Place ruler in contact with object and ensure eye is perpendicular to the scale. Use a set square to align the ruler vertically. For curved objects, use a travelling microscope.</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td class="td-num">2</td>
          <td class="td-limit"><strong>Reaction Time / Timing Error</strong><br><span style="color:var(--muted);font-size:12px;">Human error starting/stopping stopwatch.</span></td>
          <td class="td-improve">Use a light gate connected to a data logger to measure time automatically, eliminating human reaction time. Alternatively, time over multiple oscillations (e.g., 10T) and divide to reduce percentage uncertainty.</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td class="td-num">3</td>
          <td class="td-limit"><strong>Friction / Resistance in Mechanism</strong><br><span style="color:var(--muted);font-size:12px;">Friction at pivot, pulley, or surface causing systematic error.</span></td>
          <td class="td-improve">Use a frictionless pulley or air track. Lubricate pivot points. Ensure the surface is level by checking with a spirit level before each run.</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td class="td-num">4</td>
          <td class="td-limit"><strong>Oscillation / Reading Fluctuation</strong><br><span style="color:var(--muted);font-size:12px;">Meter/ammeter pointer oscillates; reading is unstable.</span></td>
          <td class="td-improve">Take the mean of several readings (e.g., 5) and calculate the average. Wait for the reading to stabilise before recording. Use a digital meter to remove pointer ambiguity.</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td class="td-num">5</td>
          <td class="td-limit"><strong>Zero Error / Systematic Offset</strong><br><span style="color:var(--muted);font-size:12px;">Instrument does not read zero when it should.</span></td>
          <td class="td-improve">Check the instrument reads zero before starting; apply a zero-correction to all readings. For a micrometer, record the zero error and subtract algebraically from all measurements.</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td class="td-num">6</td>
          <td class="td-limit"><strong>Heat / Temperature Variation</strong><br><span style="color:var(--muted);font-size:12px;">Resistance of wire changes with temperature during current flow.</span></td>
          <td class="td-improve">Use short current pulses (switch off between readings) to prevent heating of the wire. Alternatively, use a thermometer to monitor temperature and only record when it returns to room temperature.</td>
        </tr>
