  <!-- EXPLAIN QUESTIONS -->

  <h4>The "Explain" Question — Bad vs. A* Answers</h4>
  <p>Cambridge awards marks for <em>precise physical reasoning</em> using correct terminology. The examples below show exactly what separates a grade C response from an A* response.</p>

  <!-- Example 1 -->

  <div class="card card-blue" style="margin-bottom: 8px;">
    <p class="card-title">Example 1 · Superposition · "Explain how a stationary wave is formed" [3 marks]</p>
  </div>
  <div class="compare-grid" style="margin-bottom: 24px;">
    <div class="compare-bad">
      <p class="compare-label">✗ Bad Answer — Grade C</p>
      <p class="compare-text">A stationary wave forms when two waves meet. The waves combine and some places have big amplitude and some have zero amplitude. This is because of interference between the waves.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="compare-good">
      <p class="compare-label">✓ A* Answer — Full Marks</p>
      <p class="compare-text">Two waves of <mark>equal frequency and amplitude</mark> travel in <mark>opposite directions</mark> and <mark>superpose</mark>. At points where they meet <mark>in phase</mark>, <mark>constructive superposition</mark> produces antinodes with maximum amplitude 2A. At points of <mark>phase difference π rad</mark>, <mark>destructive superposition</mark> produces nodes with zero amplitude. <mark>No energy is transferred</mark> along the direction of propagation.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- Example 2 -->

  <div class="card card-blue" style="margin-bottom: 8px;">
    <p class="card-title">Example 2 · Superposition · "Explain why dark fringes appear in Young's double-slit" [3 marks]</p>
  </div>
  <div class="compare-grid" style="margin-bottom: 24px;">
    <div class="compare-bad">
      <p class="compare-label">✗ Bad Answer — Grade C</p>
      <p class="compare-text">Dark fringes form because destructive interference happens. The waves cancel each other out so there is no light.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="compare-good">
      <p class="compare-label">✓ A* Answer — Full Marks</p>
      <p class="compare-text">The two slits act as <mark>coherent sources</mark> (same frequency, constant phase difference). At dark fringe positions, the <mark>path difference</mark> from the two slits equals <mark>(n + ½)λ</mark>, where n = 0, 1, 2…. This means the waves arrive with a <mark>phase difference of π rad (antiphase)</mark>, causing <mark>destructive superposition</mark>. The amplitudes cancel, giving <mark>zero resultant amplitude</mark> and hence zero intensity.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- Example 3 -->

  <div class="card card-gold" style="margin-bottom: 8px;">
    <p class="card-title">Example 3 · Electricity · "Explain what is meant by the e.m.f. of a battery" [2 marks] + "Explain why terminal p.d. is less than e.m.f." [2 marks]</p>
  </div>
  <div class="compare-grid" style="margin-bottom: 24px;">
    <div class="compare-bad">
      <p class="compare-label">✗ Bad Answer — Grade C</p>
      <p class="compare-text">EMF is the voltage of a battery. Terminal p.d. is less because some voltage is lost inside the battery due to its resistance.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="compare-good">
      <p class="compare-label">✓ A* Answer — Full Marks</p>
      <p class="compare-text"><mark>E.m.f. is the energy converted from chemical (non-electrical) to electrical per unit charge</mark> passing through the source: E = W/Q. The terminal p.d. is less than the e.m.f. because the current I flows through the battery's <mark>internal resistance r</mark>, causing a <mark>potential drop Ir</mark> within the battery itself. Therefore: <mark>V<sub>terminal</sub> = E − Ir</mark>. This "lost voltage" appears as thermal energy in the battery.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

