    <h2 class="sec-title">Paper 12 · MCQ Traps</h2>
    <span class="sec-badge badge-mcq">3 JUN</span>
  </div>

  <p>P12 contains 40 questions in 75 minutes — that's <strong>1 min 52 sec per question</strong>. Speed comes from pattern recognition. Below are the most frequently exploited traps in the 9702 MCQ paper.</p>

  <!-- TRAP GRID -->

  <div class="trap-grid">

```
<div class="trap-card">
  <p class="trap-title">TRAP 1 — nm & μm Conversion</p>
  <p class="trap-body">
    Wavelength questions give λ in nm; formulas need m.<br>
    <strong>1 nm = 10⁻⁹ m</strong> &nbsp;|&nbsp; <strong>1 μm = 10⁻⁶ m</strong><br>
    Trap: <code>λ = 600 nm</code> entered as <code>600</code> instead of <code>6×10⁻⁷</code>.
    Always convert before substituting. Young's fringes: <code>w = λD/a</code> — if D in m, a in mm, you must convert a too.
  </p>
</div>

<div class="trap-card">
  <p class="trap-title">TRAP 2 — MeV to Joules</p>
  <p class="trap-body">
    Nuclear/particle questions give energies in MeV.<br>
    <strong>1 eV = 1.6×10⁻¹⁹ J</strong><br>
    <strong>1 MeV = 1.6×10⁻¹³ J</strong><br>
    Trap: forgetting the Mega (×10⁶) prefix. Write it as: <code>E(J) = E(MeV) × 1.6×10⁻¹³</code>
  </p>
</div>

<div class="trap-card">
  <p class="trap-title">TRAP 3 — Vector Components</p>
  <p class="trap-body">
    Always sketch the triangle. For a force F at angle θ to horizontal:<br>
    <code>F_x = F cos θ</code> &nbsp;|&nbsp; <code>F_y = F sin θ</code><br>
    Trap: swapping sin/cos when θ is measured from vertical. If θ is from <em>vertical</em>, flip: <code>F_x = F sin θ</code>. Draw it every time.
  </p>
</div>

<div class="trap-card">
  <p class="trap-title">TRAP 4 — mm² to m²</p>
  <p class="trap-body">
    Cross-sectional area A is often given in mm².<br>
    <strong>1 mm² = 10⁻⁶ m²</strong> (NOT 10⁻³!)<br>
    Trap: <code>2.5 mm² → 2.5×10⁻³ m²</code> is <em>wrong</em>.<br>
    Correct: <code>2.5 mm² = 2.5×10⁻⁶ m²</code><br>
    The Learner Guide explicitly flags this as the most common arithmetic error in 9702.
  </p>
</div>

<div class="trap-card">
  <p class="trap-title">TRAP 5 — Scalar vs Vector Signs</p>
  <p class="trap-body">
    Speed, distance, energy: always positive.<br>
    Velocity, displacement, momentum: can be negative.<br>
    Trap: taking KE as <code>½mv²</code> with a signed v — KE is always ≥ 0 so the sign of v doesn't matter for KE but <em>does</em> matter for momentum <code>p = mv</code>.
  </p>
</div>

<div class="trap-card">
  <p class="trap-title">TRAP 6 — Resistance in Parallel</p>
  <p class="trap-body">
    For two resistors in parallel:<br>
    <code>R = R₁R₂ / (R₁+R₂)</code><br>
    Trap: adding reciprocals but forgetting to take the final reciprocal.<br>
    Also: adding a resistor in <em>parallel</em> always <em>decreases</em> total resistance, even if the added resistor is large.
  </p>
</div>

<div class="trap-card">
  <p class="trap-title">TRAP 7 — g = 9.81 vs 10</p>
  <p class="trap-body">
    MCQ distractors are designed around g = 10 answers. The data sheet gives <code>g = 9.81 m s⁻²</code>. Always use 9.81 unless explicitly told otherwise. The "nice" answer is the trap.
  </p>
</div>

<div class="trap-card">
  <p class="trap-title">TRAP 8 — Period vs Frequency</p>
  <p class="trap-body">
    <code>T = 1/f</code> &nbsp;—&nbsp; if a wave has f = 400 Hz, T = 0.0025 s (not 400 s).<br>
    Trap: in wave-speed questions, <code>v = fλ</code>, not <code>v = λ/T</code> recalculated wrong. Stick to <code>v = fλ</code> directly.
  </p>
</div>

<div class="trap-card">
  <p class="trap-title">TRAP 9 — Significant Figures in MCQ</p>
  <p class="trap-body">
    MCQ answers are given to 2–3 s.f. If your calculation gives 4.9999, the answer is 5.0 (option C), not 4.9 (option B). Always round at the end, not mid-calculation. Keep full precision on calculator throughout.
  </p>
</div>

<div class="trap-card">
  <p class="trap-title">TRAP 10 — Phase Difference (rad vs degrees)</p>
  <p class="trap-body">
    9702 uses radians. "Antiphase" = π rad = 180°. "In phase" = 2π rad (or 0).<br>
    Trap: mixing degrees into a radian formula.<br>
    Path difference of λ/2 → phase difference = <code>π rad</code> ✓, not 90°.
  </p>
</div>

<div class="trap-card">
  <p class="trap-title">TRAP 11 — kWh to Joules</p>
  <p class="trap-body">
    Energy questions: <strong>1 kWh = 3.6×10⁶ J</strong><br>
    Derivation: 1 kW × 3600 s = 3.6×10⁶ J.<br>
    Trap: forgetting ×3600 and just using 1000.
  </p>
</div>

<div class="trap-card">
  <p class="trap-title">TRAP 12 — Elastic vs Inelastic</p>
  <p class="trap-body">
    In an <strong>elastic</strong> collision: KE <em>and</em> momentum are both conserved.<br>
    In an <strong>inelastic</strong> collision: only momentum is conserved. KE is not.<br>
    Trap: "perfectly inelastic" = objects stick together (maximum KE loss). This is not the same as just "inelastic".
  </p>
</div>
```

